  "output": "114 configured sources (ATS boards), each potentially returning hundreds to thousands of listings (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix boards alone are in the thousands). That confirms the SQLite diff loop matters at real scale. I have enough to write the analysis now.\n\n## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async CLI (job-board scraper → SQLite dedup → notifiers), not a web app — there's **no React and no traditional ORM**, so I've mapped your checklist to its real equivalents: SQLite round-trips instead of N+1 queries, and Python-level redundant work instead of re-renders.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-72` (`Store.diff`)\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nOne `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop. With 114 sources configured (`sources.yaml`) and boards like Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix each returning hundreds–thousands of listings per run, this is thousands of individual round-trips every pipeline run instead of one bulk read.\n\n**Fix** — load existing `(key -> content_hash)` once, diff in memory, then batch-write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, touched, to_insert, to_update = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", to_update)\n    if touched:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns thousands of round-trips into ~4 statements.\n\n### 2. Missing index — `store.py:117-119` (`added_since`)\n\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\n```\n\n`first_seen` has no index (only `company` does), so this does a full table scan + sort every time `agent.py db-new` runs. Add:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled for EVERY job\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # same\n```\n\n`_compile()` re-runs `re.escape` + `re.compile` for every keyword, for every single job. `filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, so with N jobs and M keywords that's O(N×M) recompilation calls per run.\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 4. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-76` (`content_hash` recomputed twice per changed job)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` (sha256 over 4 fields), recomputed on every access. In the changed-job path in `store.py`, it's computed once for the `!=` comparison and again inside `to_row()` for the `UPDATE`. Cheap individually, but doubled for no reason across every changed job every run.\n\n**Fix** — since `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, add an explicit cache slot instead of relying on `functools.cached_property` (which needs `__dict__`):\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity — pagination fetchers (`fetchers.py`)\n\nEvery pipeline run re-fetches full boards from scratch (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix/Google page through up to 20-40 pages each, `fetchers.py:602-738`), even though most listings are unchanged between runs (12h cron per your recent commit). There's no conditional-request support (`If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`) and no short-lived cache for the Meta token-scrape page (`fetchers.py:542`, fetched fresh every run even though `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens are likely valid for longer than one run).\n\nNot worth over-engineering given these are third-party APIs without real cache headers, but two cheap wins:\n- Pass `If-None-Match` when a prior `ETag` is stored in `meta` (per-source), skip parsing on `304`.\n- For Meta, cache the scraped tokens in `store.meta` with a short TTL (e.g. 30 min) instead of scraping `metacareers.com/jobs` on every single run.\n\n### 6. Memory leaks / long-lived state\n\nThis is a short-lived CLI process (fetch → filter → write → exit), so classic React-style leaks (dangling listeners, growing caches) don't apply, and resource cleanup already looks correct: `httpx.AsyncClient` is opened/closed via `try/finally` in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:770-787`), and `Store` is used as a context manager everywhere. Nothing to flag here.\n\n### 7. React re-renders — N/A\n\nNo frontend in this repo (no `package.json`/JSX found). If you're thinking of a different project, let me know and I'll point at that codebase instead.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 (N+1 SQLite) and #3 (regex recompilation) are the real wins since they scale with job count (thousands) and run every 12h — #2 and #4 are cheap follow-ons. Want me to implement any of these?\n",
